WEBVTT

00:01.442 --> 00:06.309
Years ago, I was greatly impacted by a series that I heard called Go Fish.

00:06.329 --> 00:08.592
And the pastor, he began his message by saying this.

00:09.153 --> 00:12.959
When Jesus first called the disciples, he made them a promise.

00:13.540 --> 00:14.822
It was an odd promise.

00:14.942 --> 00:18.707
He told them that if they followed him, he would make them fishers of men.

00:19.408 --> 00:21.211
And they didn't really understand what that meant.

00:21.832 --> 00:23.314
They weren't intrigued by that.

00:23.490 --> 00:26.995
They followed him for their own selfish reasons, like many of us do.

00:27.415 --> 00:32.102
Nevertheless, Jesus was faithful to what he had promised, and it is what happened.

00:32.542 --> 00:36.548
They became fishers of men because they took the teachings of Jesus.

00:36.848 --> 00:47.282
They shared it with other men and women who shared it with other men and women, and eventually here we are today, celebrating who God is and what he has done for us through his son, Jesus.

00:48.194 --> 01:02.328
It is incredible that that was how the number of believers has grown because for many people today, the idea of talking about our faith and more specifically talking about Jesus is uncomfortable and challenging.

01:03.168 --> 01:16.121
And depending on how you were raised, maybe you even think it isn't right to tell someone else about what you believe or to try and to compel or to convince someone to believe what you believe because faith is private.

01:16.741 --> 01:17.362
It's personal.

01:18.082 --> 01:24.895
You think, I don't want to offend or I don't want to intrude on another's right to believe what they want to believe.

01:25.917 --> 01:28.822
And yet I assume most of us are so glad.

01:28.842 --> 01:31.608
We're just so grateful that someone told us about Jesus.

01:32.810 --> 01:37.138
And yet they also think, but just don't expect me to tell someone else.

01:38.370 --> 01:49.182
You know, you're so thankful that you were invited to Alpha or that someone gave you that book, that someone took that time to have conversations with you so that you could explore your questions.

01:49.582 --> 01:55.869
You could wrestle through the obstacles that you faced and they helped lead you to inviting Jesus to become the Lord of your life.

01:55.949 --> 01:59.393
But to do this for someone else, it just doesn't sit right.

02:00.835 --> 02:03.698
Maybe you think that's what a pastor ought to do.

02:04.450 --> 02:20.639
Additionally, here at Sanctus, we talk a lot about gift-based ministry, so there are individuals who are spiritually gifted as evangelists, and they're the ones that find it the easiest to talk about Jesus, so we could just leave the job to them, right?

02:23.464 --> 02:28.754
Who was Jesus talking to when he gave his last command before he ascended into heaven?

02:29.794 --> 02:37.524
Matthew 28, 18 to 20, it says, then Jesus came to them and said, all authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me.

02:38.425 --> 02:49.699
Therefore go and make disciples of all nations, baptizing them in the name of the Father and the Son and the Holy Spirit and teaching them to obey everything I have commanded you.

02:50.541 --> 02:56.568
And surely I am with you always to the very end of the age.

02:56.588 --> 02:57.970
If it wasn't directed to all,

02:58.530 --> 03:06.799
Don't you think that Jesus would have clarified saying specifically, okay, those of you who have the education or the gifting, you're the ones here over here.

03:07.540 --> 03:10.123
Yeah, you're the ones to go and make disciples.

03:12.045 --> 03:18.652
No, he was speaking to anyone currently following him and to everyone who will ever follow him.

03:20.394 --> 03:25.720
Wait, you say, but doesn't scripture say that God reveals himself through creation?

03:25.760 --> 03:27.922
So why do we have to talk about him?

03:29.122 --> 03:32.025
Well, for starters, you are a part of creation.

03:33.907 --> 03:36.809
If you turn on your television, look at your Facebook feed.

03:37.090 --> 03:39.872
There's no denying that there's a lot of brokenness in this world.

03:39.912 --> 03:45.478
We're in need of healing and restoration, and people are looking for a way out of the brokenness.

03:46.459 --> 03:49.622
But again, you may ask, why do we have to talk about it?

03:50.683 --> 03:57.970
Christianity provides the only solution that can actually lift us out of brokenness into wholeness.

03:58.562 --> 04:02.126
The obstacle then is Christianity is not intuitive.

04:03.087 --> 04:04.489
One pastor worded it like this.

04:05.330 --> 04:18.144
This is not something that you can sit out and creation and arrive at or come to conclusions by yourself because Christianity is not simply a theology or a philosophy or a morality or a set of ethics or a set of values.

04:18.444 --> 04:22.609
Christianity is something that is grounded and founded in history.

04:22.949 --> 04:25.072
Christianity is not a belief system.

04:25.632 --> 04:26.994
It's an about an event.

04:27.938 --> 04:32.804
The only way for someone to know about something that has happened in history is for someone to talk about it.

04:33.645 --> 04:42.175
For the early church members in Acts, the reason they had to talk about it was because this event was one that they had seen, one that they had heard.

04:44.197 --> 04:50.425
But even today, how can someone become a disciple if they've not heard Jesus' message?

04:51.066 --> 04:54.770
How do they hear it if someone does not tell and explain it to them?

04:55.970 --> 04:58.414
Now you may agree, all of that does make sense.

04:59.055 --> 05:02.380
Followers of Jesus, they have a responsibility of sharing the good news.

05:03.602 --> 05:07.188
And yet, do you still shy away from the responsibility?

05:08.310 --> 05:17.565
I think the reason that we don't speak more boldly or more intentionally about Jesus to our unsaved family and friends is because of one word, fear.

05:19.287 --> 05:20.690
We are afraid.

05:21.511 --> 05:23.474
And we may express it differently.

05:23.650 --> 05:24.932
What if I say it wrong?

05:24.952 --> 05:26.414
What if I get made fun of?

05:26.594 --> 05:27.936
What if I lose that friendship?

05:28.156 --> 05:29.257
What if I lose my job?

05:29.738 --> 05:30.078
What if?

05:30.218 --> 05:30.619
What if?

05:32.421 --> 05:37.648
But let's remember, the followers of Jesus, they were a bunch of cowards too initially.

05:38.910 --> 05:43.175
One time this little girl comes up to Peter and asks him, are you one of them?

05:43.536 --> 05:45.098
Peter starts cursing up and down.

05:45.218 --> 05:46.319
I never knew the guy.

05:46.359 --> 05:48.562
He was afraid.

05:49.250 --> 05:53.957
The rest of the disciples, they had fled and scattered long before Peter had denied Christ.

05:54.578 --> 05:56.380
They certainly had something to be afraid of.

05:56.941 --> 06:01.147
Officials had just taken their leader and killed him by hanging him on a cross.

06:02.108 --> 06:04.632
They had more to fear than many of us will ever face.

06:05.633 --> 06:08.277
All of them were afraid to be associated with them.

06:09.399 --> 06:12.744
But something happened that changed all of that.

06:14.146 --> 06:17.170
This fall, we've been looking at the early church in the Book of Acts

06:17.378 --> 06:20.041
It provides many examples for us to follow.

06:20.502 --> 06:27.931
And for the past three weeks, we've heard about how the church grew from 150 to 3000 to 10,000 in a really short period of time.

06:28.872 --> 06:31.976
Something happened that emboldened the disciples.

06:32.677 --> 06:37.964
Instead of running away, they obeyed Jesus' last command to go and make disciples.

06:39.225 --> 06:42.930
Because they saw and heard, they spoke.

06:44.130 --> 06:46.934
Let's dive into where Pastor John left off last week.

06:46.994 --> 06:52.542
And if you have a Bible with you, take a moment to find Acts, chapter four, verse 23.

06:54.505 --> 06:58.812
Before we read, I'm just gonna bring us up to speed on what's happened leading up to this verse.

06:59.953 --> 07:04.440
Now the first four books of the New Testament, they tell us about how Jesus died on the cross.

07:04.840 --> 07:06.984
Three days later, he rose from the dead.

07:07.524 --> 07:11.330
The resurrected Jesus, he returned to his disciples.

07:12.051 --> 07:14.034
He spent time with his fearful followers.

07:14.466 --> 07:24.466
reinstating them, teaching them, reassuring them that even though they can expect trials, roadblocks to their mission, he was going to send a counselor to be with them.

07:24.866 --> 07:26.269
And then he ascended into heaven.

07:27.131 --> 07:31.960
That's what Christians believe because the Bible says, Jesus is now at the right hand of his father.

07:33.223 --> 07:36.850
The individuals that had spent the most time with Jesus.

07:38.210 --> 07:44.381
This is when they start to feel this duty bound to talk about him regularly.

07:44.822 --> 07:47.426
And two of them, Peter and John, they go up to the temple to pray.

07:47.887 --> 07:50.993
A lame man was begging at the gate and he asks them for some money.

07:51.033 --> 07:55.561
And Peter says, silver or gold, I do not have, but what I have, I'll give to you.

07:55.581 --> 07:59.047
In the name of Jesus Christ of Nazareth, walk.

08:00.029 --> 08:00.850
He heals the guy.

08:01.122 --> 08:03.164
The man had never walked since birth.

08:03.204 --> 08:03.925
He jumps up.

08:03.965 --> 08:04.966
He's leaping around.

08:05.006 --> 08:06.027
He goes into the temple.

08:06.308 --> 08:07.569
He's clinging on to Peter.

08:07.809 --> 08:12.094
He says, here's the guy that healed me and Peter, an uneducated fisherman.

08:12.755 --> 08:14.677
He had given a speech on the day of Pentecost.

08:14.697 --> 08:16.920
So he's getting used to this public speaking thing.

08:17.420 --> 08:19.002
He gives a mini sermon about Jesus.

08:19.843 --> 08:29.714
And the people in charge of the temple, they aren't happy because they feel like maybe how some of you feel, hey, if you want to believe in Jesus, that's fine.

08:29.826 --> 08:31.788
for you, but just don't talk about it.

08:33.830 --> 08:43.341
It reminds me one day my son, he came home from school, said that he was told that he could talk about Jesus at home with his friends or with his family.

08:45.383 --> 08:49.388
See, you can talk about God, that's safe, but just don't talk about Jesus.

08:50.589 --> 08:54.594
And you can talk with those who believe the same thing as you, but don't talk about it in public.

08:56.015 --> 08:58.578
I think his teacher, like many people do,

08:59.298 --> 09:00.259
find it offensive.

09:01.762 --> 09:05.968
Well, Peter and John, they offended the temple leaders enough that they were arrested.

09:06.008 --> 09:07.049
They spent a night in jail.

09:07.670 --> 09:09.112
They were brought before the Sanhedrin.

09:09.432 --> 09:11.495
This is very important institution.

09:11.555 --> 09:14.299
It was made up of the high priest, the priest class, and the scholars.

09:14.860 --> 09:18.105
They had jurisdiction over every single Jew on the earth.

09:18.726 --> 09:21.890
And they tell Peter and John, you have to stop speaking about Jesus.

09:23.492 --> 09:26.256
Peter takes the opportunity to preach another sermon.

09:26.757 --> 09:27.378
He says,

09:27.586 --> 09:30.449
We've got to continue to speak about what we've seen and heard.

09:31.010 --> 09:33.472
And then he directly confronts their beliefs.

09:33.512 --> 09:38.638
He says this, Acts 4 verse 12 says, salvation is found in no one else.

09:39.219 --> 09:44.504
For there is no other name under heaven given to man by which we must be saved.

09:46.226 --> 09:52.993
Now they knew that God is Savior, but these two men were attributing the same title here to Jesus.

09:54.115 --> 09:57.298
The Jews theology, it had become threatened.

09:57.794 --> 09:59.996
But this isn't the only thing that angers them.

10:00.637 --> 10:09.565
The rulers and the authorities are angry because Peter declared as well, those who don't listen to Jesus, you will be completely cut off from his people.

10:11.167 --> 10:14.890
This is profoundly threatening to their roles as leaders in Israel.

10:15.210 --> 10:20.495
And as Pastor John said last week, God's extraordinary move, it threatens the status quo.

10:21.356 --> 10:23.778
God threatens what has been long established.

10:24.659 --> 10:27.602
Those places where God had moved so long ago,

10:28.290 --> 10:31.473
It had hardened into tradition and institution.

10:32.915 --> 10:43.026
Now, in spite of their anger, threatening Peter and John was all the leaders did at that moment because the healed man and those who had witnessed this healing were present still.

10:44.027 --> 10:47.251
So it's too soon for them to do anything more and Peter and John are just released.

10:48.332 --> 10:48.432
Okay.

10:49.073 --> 10:50.474
That brings us to our text today.

10:50.975 --> 10:53.938
Acts 4 verse 23, on their release,

10:54.210 --> 10:59.055
Peter and John went back to their own people and reported all that the chief priests and the elders had said to them.

11:00.776 --> 11:01.877
Everybody needs their own people.

11:02.238 --> 11:03.159
That's where this comes from.

11:03.619 --> 11:06.061
If you don't have your people, life is too difficult on your own.

11:06.101 --> 11:06.502
So come on.

11:07.102 --> 11:10.786
You need to work at identifying your people, your people.

11:10.826 --> 11:13.689
That's a community of mutually supportive friends.

11:13.889 --> 11:16.571
One, ones who will encourage your discipleship.

11:17.452 --> 11:23.378
Then let us know who you're meeting with because we call those connect groups and we care a lot about whether or not you're in one.

11:24.578 --> 11:25.379
Acts 4, 24.

11:26.220 --> 11:30.565
When they heard this, they raised their voices together in prayer to God.

11:31.566 --> 11:34.349
So once they shared what had happened, they held a prayer meeting.

11:35.150 --> 11:40.276
They didn't rush to go and find some human counsel, but instead they looked for help through prayer.

11:41.598 --> 11:43.179
That's the pattern of the early church.

11:43.680 --> 11:46.303
And it's critical that we don't miss how important this is.

11:47.404 --> 11:48.946
When life throws us a curveball,

11:49.090 --> 11:59.685
Sure, we can talk about God, but if we don't actually turn our attention and talk to God, the greatest benefit of coming together has just been neglected, where two or three believers are gathered together.

11:59.745 --> 12:01.468
Jesus promises his presence.

12:01.848 --> 12:04.532
So why not invite him to get involved?

12:06.095 --> 12:09.399
Their news drives the believers immediately to their knees.

12:10.641 --> 12:13.705
Growing up, my parents had a sign that hung on our kitchen wall.

12:13.726 --> 12:16.850
It said, the family that prays together stays together.

12:18.466 --> 12:19.387
There's something to that.

12:20.208 --> 12:27.715
You know, if we're unable to pray together because of disunity, we need to struggle, struggle through whatever is causing that disunity.

12:27.995 --> 12:29.136
We've got to work it out.

12:29.697 --> 12:34.141
And in this situation, unity, that's what enabled the believers to pray.

12:34.181 --> 12:36.843
It says they raise their voices together.

12:36.883 --> 12:42.429
Now that would be pretty miraculous if they just shouted in unison the same words at the same time.

12:42.489 --> 12:48.274
So my guess is more than likely one person probably prayed the whole community unified in spirit.

12:48.706 --> 12:53.333
So that means they were in agreement, maybe nodding their heads saying, yes, amen.

12:54.415 --> 12:57.660
Because when you do these things, it helps you to concentrate better.

12:58.160 --> 13:01.486
It helps you to actually participate in the prayer of someone else.

13:03.068 --> 13:06.113
Now, they could have prayed something similar to what we usually pray.

13:06.153 --> 13:09.999
Thank you so much for this day, Lord, please help me, bless me, protect me.

13:10.059 --> 13:13.203
It could have, but watch this.

13:13.724 --> 13:17.490
Acts 4, 24, sovereign Lord, they said,

13:17.954 --> 13:21.019
You made the heavens and the earth and the sea and everything in them.

13:23.142 --> 13:26.067
Sovereign Lord, that's how they begin.

13:26.307 --> 13:33.278
They begin by acknowledging him as the absolute authority, tying that to his position as creator of everything.

13:34.079 --> 13:38.526
That's what allows him to function as master over his creation.

13:38.766 --> 13:43.914
So the implication is that the one who created the world is more powerful than those he created.

13:45.297 --> 13:46.258
In the New Testament,

13:47.074 --> 13:52.042
The term sovereign Lord, it's used three times, each for God and for Jesus.

13:53.264 --> 13:57.731
Their prayer, it's certainly desperate, but the tone is expectant.

13:57.972 --> 14:00.876
The words that follow are biblically informed.

14:02.339 --> 14:06.125
You spoke by the Holy Spirit through the mouth of your servant, our Father David.

14:06.405 --> 14:08.649
They're quoting the opening words to the second Psalm.

14:10.252 --> 14:14.098
They say, why do the nations rage and the people's plot in vain?

14:14.530 --> 14:19.979
The kings of the earth rise up and the rulers band together against the Lord and against his anointed one.

14:21.621 --> 14:28.312
David, he wrote these words because the rulers, the people at that time, they were conspiring together against him with Saul.

14:28.693 --> 14:31.317
They were against David being their new king.

14:31.878 --> 14:37.527
And clearly, David, he has reason to complain because the kings, the people, they're making plans for war.

14:38.548 --> 14:42.034
In this verse, he references the Lord's anointed one.

14:42.722 --> 14:49.670
Originally, David was writing about himself, but it's also prophetic about what was happening in the time of the apostles.

14:50.531 --> 15:00.142
As early as the middle of the first century BC, anointed one, that was interpreted to mean the deliverer of David's line, the Messiah.

15:00.162 --> 15:07.430
And the apostles, they were present when God acclaimed Jesus as Messiah, with the words, you are my son during his baptism.

15:08.051 --> 15:10.834
That's the exact line that's used in Psalms 2, verse 7.

15:11.138 --> 15:15.785
So they quote this song because it was being fulfilled in real time for them.

15:16.767 --> 15:20.973
They knew that their present opposition, that was anticipated in Scripture.

15:21.253 --> 15:24.378
And the disciples' lives, they were at risk now more than ever.

15:25.600 --> 15:28.304
And then they just give this little explanation of what they're facing.

15:28.624 --> 15:30.587
So Acts 4, it's 27, we're at.

15:31.649 --> 15:37.618
Indeed, Herod, Pontius Pilate, they met together with the Gentiles and the people of Israel in this city.

15:38.274 --> 15:41.678
to conspire against your holy servant, Jesus, whom you anointed."

15:42.819 --> 15:45.041
So Herod, this is Herod Antipas.

15:45.742 --> 15:53.571
His dad, Herod the Great, had tried killing Jesus as a two-year-old by killing all the little boys in the area when Jesus was born.

15:53.831 --> 16:01.319
So this Herod was the son, and he's the one who had killed John the Baptist, and he had helped Jesus go to his death.

16:02.060 --> 16:04.022
Pilate, that's Caesar's representative.

16:04.222 --> 16:05.303
He was also a part of this.

16:05.404 --> 16:07.666
Gentiles, that refers to the Romans.

16:08.098 --> 16:13.204
and the people of Israel, the people of God, the Jewish nation, God's people and their leaders.

16:14.105 --> 16:15.066
They're included too.

16:15.907 --> 16:18.830
This list tells us all people.

16:20.011 --> 16:23.475
Everyone, we're all responsible for the death of God's son.

16:25.558 --> 16:31.244
Verse 28, they did what your power and will had decided beforehand should happen.

16:32.325 --> 16:36.370
So the way that this is phrased is reminding us again, the Lord is sovereign.

16:36.802 --> 16:40.846
He allows events to happen and yet they're filtered through his hands.

16:41.647 --> 16:48.895
And what's also clear about this is that throughout history, the powers of this world have stood against the cause of God and of Christ.

16:49.835 --> 16:52.098
Let's face it, the enemy is powerful.

16:53.199 --> 16:57.583
But because God is sovereign, evil is limited.

16:58.124 --> 17:03.890
One commentator, he stated it this way, he says, Satan is on the loose, but he's on a leash.

17:04.866 --> 17:07.329
See, God foresaw the evil plan.

17:07.389 --> 17:09.251
He planned to do something good out of it.

17:09.671 --> 17:11.333
And actually, not just something good.

17:11.433 --> 17:15.357
He did the greatest thing that ever happened in the history of all humanity.

17:19.441 --> 17:23.505
The opposition that Jesus faced was now extended to the new believers.

17:24.607 --> 17:26.849
They truly were following in his footsteps.

17:27.810 --> 17:31.794
Real discipleship has always been and continues to be costly.

17:32.322 --> 17:39.791
in places like Pakistan, Syria, Bangladesh, North Korea, Christian persecution, it regularly means Christians are martyred.

17:40.652 --> 17:52.607
And according to the International Society for Human Rights, a secular observatory that's based in Frankfurt, Germany, they said that 80% of all acts of religious discrimination in the world today are directed at Christians.

17:53.508 --> 17:57.673
That makes Christians by far the most persecuted religious body on the planet.

17:59.115 --> 18:01.938
And when faced with persecution, the early church in Acts

18:02.210 --> 18:06.820
they turn to desperate, biblically informed, expectant prayer.

18:08.102 --> 18:14.977
You've certainly heard it here said before, but prayer is a guaranteed place and encounter between the divine and the human.

18:16.079 --> 18:17.342
Pay attention to what happens next.

18:18.264 --> 18:23.154
Verse 29, Now Lord, consider their threats and

18:23.298 --> 18:24.380
Okay, here comes the request.

18:24.820 --> 18:29.207
Lord, consider, look at, listen to, take note, and act accordingly.

18:29.488 --> 18:42.368
God, please, would you think seriously about the people, the leaders, the forces behind them that are inspiring them, all the threats that they're making, they're appealing now to the justice of God, and then they pray.

18:42.408 --> 18:44.532
Enable your servants.

18:45.754 --> 18:50.962
Enable your servants to speak your word with great boldness.

18:51.394 --> 18:57.844
Stretch out your hand to heal and perform signs and wonders through the name of your Holy servant Jesus.

18:59.206 --> 19:05.796
The request that they make is not for wisdom, not for protection or for favor with the authorities.

19:06.096 --> 19:13.928
Now, all of these would have been really appropriate requests, of course, but instead the request is for boldness.

19:15.430 --> 19:20.498
They asked for boldness because they were afraid, fear,

19:20.834 --> 19:24.640
It's just a natural human emotion to danger or to the unknown.

19:24.740 --> 19:26.542
And they were definitely facing both.

19:27.924 --> 19:32.832
They asked for boldness to speak God's message without fearing the consequences.

19:34.254 --> 19:38.059
Notice it's not their own words that they pray to speak boldly.

19:38.380 --> 19:43.447
They needed boldness to obey what Christ commanded them, to take His word and to go to the world.

19:45.130 --> 19:46.832
I believe that's what it means to be missional.

19:47.734 --> 19:50.738
We recently added the word missional to our church's vision statement.

19:51.362 --> 19:58.890
because we see our purpose as being rooted in God's mission to call people into a reconciled relationship with himself.

19:59.831 --> 20:07.860
Some would say the church has a mission, but a more correct statement would be the mission has a church.

20:09.342 --> 20:12.045
We are God's instruments to advance his mission.

20:13.527 --> 20:16.150
Would you say that you're living on mission?

20:17.371 --> 20:19.954
Well, who's mission?

20:20.130 --> 20:29.903
The second request that they ask was that as the community that proclaims the word, as they face opposition, God, would you please match it?

20:30.223 --> 20:32.025
Match it with visible activity.

20:32.486 --> 20:41.157
Match it, Lord, with your sovereign ability to heal because healings and deliverances, they open the door to introduce people to Jesus.

20:42.238 --> 20:48.146
Just one day prior, Peter and John, they were given this great opportunity to preach the gospel after the lame man was healed.

20:48.354 --> 20:58.784
And they knew how much the effectiveness of their preaching was helped by the healings and the other miraculous signs that were worked by the Lord through the name of Jesus.

20:59.405 --> 21:02.808
And so they just simply pray, could more of this continue?

21:02.848 --> 21:05.050
The name of Jesus.

21:06.071 --> 21:07.713
That's not some magical formula.

